00:09:58,360 --> 00:09:59,600
 This is not really waiting.

215
00:09:59,600 --> 00:10:01,960
 What this is doing, when you see the await,

216
00:10:01,960 --> 00:10:05,160
 it's almost like the code has been broken into two halves.

217
00:10:05,160 --> 00:10:06,800
 It runs this half.

218
00:10:06,800 --> 00:10:08,840
 And then when you say await,

219
00:10:08,840 --> 00:10:11,120
 it holds on to this half, right?

220
00:10:11,120 --> 00:10:13,200
 Grabs the rest of the code

221
00:10:13,200 --> 00:10:15,840
 and makes that be an event to be run.

222
00:10:15,840 --> 00:10:20,360
 And so this await syntax does all that splitting of code,

223
00:10:20,360 --> 00:10:22,080
 creating the event,

224
00:10:22,080 --> 00:10:25,380
 indicating that the last half of this code

225
00:10:25,380 --> 00:10:27,320
 is supposed to be run as a result of the event.

226
00:10:27,320 --> 00:10:31,400
 So it's basically a way to kinda split this code in half.

227
00:10:31,400 --> 00:10:34,720
 And then when the event finishes, it's gonna pick up here.

228
00:10:34,720 --> 00:10:36,840
 But we get to pretend it's procedural.

229
00:10:36,840 --> 00:10:39,420
 We get to pretend we're in Python.

